The two Poland
The European Parliament has recently condemned the attempt by the Polish government to strip Bronislaw Geremek of his parliamentary mandate.
A former leader of Solidarity, a former political prisoner and former Minister of Foreign Affairs - he led Poland's accession to NATO - Geremek refused to sign another statement stating that he was not a secret police agent during the communist era.
European parliamentarians spoke of a "witch hunt" in connection with the behavior of the Polish government and Geremek stated that the lustration law [décommunisation] constitutes a threat to public liberties.
In response, Polish Prime Minister Jaroslaw Kaczynski accused him of "harming the motherland" and stirring up anti-Polish sentiment.
The communists used the same words when Geremek criticized their abuse of power.
A decision by the Constitutional Tribunal dated May 11 largely invalidated the lustration law, allowing Geremek to retain his seat in the European Parliament, at least for the time being.
But this law is part of a general policy of the Polish government, which has only one purpose: to weaken the institutions and the democratic fabric of the country.
What is happening in Poland, the country where the collapse of communism began?
Each revolution goes through two phases: first a struggle for freedom, then a fight for power.
The first is an emancipation of the human soul by which man expresses what is best in him, while the second frees the worst: envy, intrigue, greed, suspicion, and the desire for vengeance.
The revolution triggered by the Polish Solidarity union took an unusual course.
Solidarity, forced into clandestinity when martial law was decreed in December 1981, survived seven years of repression to reappear in the open in 1989, in the wake of the "perestroika" initiated by Gorbachev.
During the negotiations that brought an end to the communist regime, Solidarity and the reformist wing of the communist government reached a compromise that opened the way to the peaceful dismantling of the communist dictatorship throughout the Soviet bloc.
Solidarity adopted a compromising attitude rather than one of vengeance, preferring the idea of a Poland for all rather than a divided country between all-powerful winners and oppressed losers.
Since 1989, there have been changes in government, but the country has remained stable.
But not everyone followed this path.
Today, Poland is governed by a coalition of revenge-seekers from the post-Solidarity era, provincial post-communist troublemakers, xenophobic and anti-Semitic groups, heirs to pre-war chauvinism, and the circles surrounding Radio Maryja, mouthpiece of ethno-clerical fundamentalism.
Alarming signs are visible everywhere: the authority of the Justice is being undermined, the independence of the Constitutional Tribunal is being called into question, officials are being bought, and the prosecutor's function is being politicized.
Society suffers a repressive regulation every day.
Why all this?
Each successful revolution has its winners and losers.
The Polish revolution brought public freedoms, but also more delinquency, the market economy, but also the risks of bankruptcy for companies, and high unemployment, as well as the emergence of a dynamic middle class, accompanied by a growing gap in income.
It opened Poland to Europe, but it also induced the fear of the foreigner and the fear of a mass invasion of Western culture.
For the losers of the 1989 Polish revolution, freedom is accompanied by many uncertainties.
In large enterprises, Solidarity workers have become victims of the freedoms they have conquered.
In the communist prison universe, people were considered to belong to the state, but the latter took care of them.
There is no one to take care of us in a world of freedom.
It is in this atmosphere of anxiety that the current government is governing, combining the conservative potion of George Bush with the centralism of Vladimir Putin.
The veterans of Solidarity thought that the end of the dictatorship would allow them to reach the firmament.
But the perpetrators among the communists have not been punished and the virtuous Solidarity militants have not been rewarded.
Moreover, the sense of injustice has given birth to resentment, envy, and a vengeful energy directed not only at the former enemies but also at old friends who seemed to be getting away with it.
The losers did not want to acknowledge that the conquest of freedom was the greatest success of Poland in 300 years.
For them, Poland remained a country governed by the communist security apparatus.
This Poland was in need of a moral revolution that would ensure that crimes went unpunished, virtue was rewarded, and injustices were rectified.
After their victory in the general elections of 2005, the political parties of the losers chose a method: a great purging.
According to first estimates, lustration should take 17 years and affect 700,000 people.
A list of names has been found in the archives of the security services; it will be made public.
And the 700,000 people promised to lustration must declare that they did not collaborate with the security services.
Those who refuse or make a false declaration must be fired and barred from practicing their profession for ten years.

The cardinal Dziwisz of Cracow reminds us that there is no place "for revenge, vengeance, lack of respect for human dignity and baseless accusations".
Never since the fall of communism, a cardinal has used such strong words.
Should this lustration have taken place at the beginning of Poland's transformation? The purpose of this peaceful revolution was freedom, sovereignty, and economic reforms, not a hunt for suspects, proven or not, of having belonged to the secret police.
If this hunt had been organized in 1990, neither Leszek Balcerowicz's economic reforms, nor the establishment of the rule of law would have been possible.
And Poland would not be a member of NATO, nor of the European Union.
Today, two Poland are facing each other.
The Poland of suspicion, fear, and revenge fights the Poland of hope, courage, and dialogue.
This Poland - made of openness and tolerance, that of Jean-Paul II and Czeslaw Milisz, of my friends in the clandestinity and in prison - must prevail.
I believe that the Poles will once again defend their right to be treated with dignity.
The decision of the Constitutional Tribunal leaves hope that the second phase of the Polish revolution will destroy neither what gave birth to it, the will to freedom, nor what it has engendered, a democratic state.
